                BUFEX, BUFMX, BUFSX, BUFIX: Top Buffalo Funds for Retirement            


    By Brian Mathews | Updated August 24, 2016 — 3:01 PM EDT    






Share


















































Buffalo Funds is based in Milwaukee, Wisconsin. The founder, John Kornitzer, created the company in 1994 and has built a team of dedicated and experienced professionals to lead its fund lineup. Buffalo Funds has 10 different funds in the areas of income, domestic equity and international equity. Buffalo Funds provides its clients with a long-term investment option through patient investing backed by intelligent research.
Even though Buffalo Funds only offers 10 different options for investors, retirement diversification is still possible since most funds are style-specific according to market capitalization. An investor could use the following five funds to establish a well-diversified retirement portfolio.
Buffalo Large Cap Fund (BUFEX)
Buffalo Funds' flagship Large Cap Fund can be a core holding of any retirement portfolio. The fund's portfolio manager, Elizabeth Jones, has been at the helm since 2007. The fund looks to invest in large-cap stocks with strong management teams, little debt, free cash flow and other attractive valuations. As of Sept. 30, 2015, the fund has total assets of $49 million and it has an expense ratio of 0.94%.
The fund has given investors an average return of 7.78% on a 10-year basis. Although this is slightly less than the benchmark’s Russell 1000 Growth Index return of 8.09%, the fund takes considerably less risk. The fund has a beta of 0.88 and an alpha of 4.41, indicating that it performs better on a risk-adjusted basis than the benchmark. Investors looking for exposure to the large-cap sector with a good track record should look to the Buffalo Large Cap Fund.
Buffalo Mid Cap Fund (BUFMX)
Buffalo’s Mid Cap Fund is managed by Dave Carlsen and Bob Male using a comprehensive team approach. The managers look to maintain a fund with 50 to 70 stock positions of mid-cap companies that are fundamentally strong. The fund looks to purchase stocks that have been negatively affected by short-term events or that are underappreciated in value. Currently, the fund's total assets equal $405 million and it has an expense ratio of 1.01%.
The fund has performed on an average level over the long term. Over the 10-year average, the fund annualizes at 7.19%, which is 0.9% lower than the benchmark. The fund’s largest holdings are Hospira, Lions Gate Entertainment and WhiteWave Foods. The managers look to take advantage of positive forward trends, as it is overweight in the financial and industrials sectors of the market.
Buffalo Small Cap Fund (BUFSX)
The small-cap asset class is historically one of the most volatile investment classes, yet it has the potential to provide the greatest returns. The Buffalo Small Cap Fund is managed by Jamie Cuellar and Bob Male, and it holds $850 million in assets. Like its other equity funds, the Small Cap Fund looks to invest in 50 to 70 stocks that are fundamentally strong.
The Small Cap Fund has a superior longer-term track record, but it has underperformed in more recent years. Since the fund's inception in 1998, the fund has produced an average return of 10.94%. This is far above the benchmark's return of 4.89%. However, when looking at the five-, three- and one-year averages, the benchmark has outperformed. This volatile asset class is best held with a long-term perspective.
Buffalo International Fund (BUFIX)
The International Fund is the only fund in Buffalo's lineup with international exposure. Nicole and William Kornitzer run the fund; they have both been with the firm since 2004. The International Fund screens premier international growth companies with similar criteria as the domestic equity funds. The managers invest in 65 to 85 positions with a specific country analysis that helps frame risk versus reward for each position.
The fund has significantly outperformed its benchmark over every average period. The five-year annual average produced a return of 4.05%, versus the benchmark’s 1.82%. The fund also does well in terms of managing risk, with a beta of 0.78 and an alpha of 3.51. Investors seeking international exposure with excellent risk-adjusted performance should consider the Buffalo International Fund.
Buffalo High Yield Fund (BUFHX)
As the only true fixed income fund in Buffalo's lineup, the High Yield Fund rounds out the list for a diversified portfolio. Managed by a team of four Certified Financial Analysts (CFAs), the fund looks to generate current income while growing over the long term. The fund consists of 67% corporate bonds, 15% convertible bonds, and the rest in dividend and preferred stocks.
Overall, the fund has performed well versus the benchmark index on a long-term basis. On the three-year average, the fund annualizes a total return of 4.79% versus the benchmark's return of 3.46%. This return comes at a lower risk level, with the fund having a beta of 0.55 and an alpha of 2.81. Investors seeking a high current income of 3.46% should take a look at the Buffalo High Yield Fund.









  


 









STOCKS: 
BUFEX, BUFMX, BUFSX, BUFIX 




































